The performance is one in which I’m considering the end of the World from a far out, journalistic perspective- and when I thought of who that person would be I thought of the Queer who is told they don’t exist and are unnatural and have chosen that. So this idea that I’ve chosen to be unnatural and not exist- and in my non-existence, am viewing what we are in, in terms of this global crisis.

“The thesis of these books was that the most important thing was Mother Earth, but that she couldn’t exist without Father Sun. I’m thinking about the Moon.”

“Nowhere Apparent” a film written & performed by me / directed by @jeremyjacob___  premieres February 28th on @allartstv. While a short it has taken a long time, and includes research from our AIDS Oral History project with @jeromerobbinsdancedivision at @nypl_lpa and excerpts of my solo “IS GLOBAL WARMING CAMP? and other forms of theatrical distance for the end of the world” in the @marcswanson exhibition at @massmoca. 
Commissioned by All Arts for their “Past Present Future” dance film festival, and I am so happy to have been selected with @jabjaytay and @omari_wiles film : “Our Name Our Legacy” which premieres March 7th. 
Link in @allartstv for more info.

Artist @jackferver explores a generation of choreographers and dancers lost to the AIDS epidemic in “Nowhere Apparent.”

Created with filmmaker @jeremyjacob__, Ferver and Jacob interrogate themes of queer isolation and feeling of loss in the wake of a failed response to the crisis through theatrical vignettes and performance footage.

Presented as part of the #PastPresentFuture festival, catch the premiere tonight on our NYC-local channel at 8 p.m. or any time nationwide on the free ALL ARTS app and website. Find more information at the link in our bio!

Link in bio for 12/7 screening + talk of NOWHERE APPARENT at @nypl_lpa with @allartstv artistic director @originaljamking, who commissioned the film for Past Present Future (where the film is steaming). Written/choreographed by me & directed/edited by @jeremyjacob___ . Forever gratitude to @jeromerobbinsdancedivision for our AIDS Oral History fellowship. 
@papermagazine describes the film as “a poetic meditation on queer isolation and feelings of abandonment by a generation of potential parental figures as a result of a failed response to the AIDS epidemic. Ferver’s performance is intense and mesmerizing, vacillating between a methodical calm and being on the precipice of a full-on breakdown, reconciling personal trauma with historic injustice in a way that is viscerally captivating.”
